<p><b>Big <i>O</i> notation</b> is a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wi=
ki/Mathematical_notation" title=3D"Mathematical notation">mathematical nota=
tion</a> that describes the approximate size of a <a href=3D"https://en.wik=
ipedia.org/wiki/Function_(mathematics)" title=3D"Function (mathematics)">fu=
nction</a> on a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Domain_of_a_functi=
on" title=3D"Domain of a function">domain</a>. Big O is a member of a <a hr=
ef=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Big_O_notation#Related_asymptotic_notat=
ions">family of notations</a> invented by German mathematicians <a href=3D"=
https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Paul_Gustav_Heinrich_Bachmann" title=3D"Paul =
Gustav Heinrich Bachmann">Paul Bachmann</a> and <sup id=3D"cite_ref-Bachman=
n_1-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Big_O_n=
otation#cite_note-Bachmann-1"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>1<span c=
lass=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.or=
g/wiki/Edmund_Landau" title=3D"Edmund Landau">Edmund Landau</a>=20
<sup id=3D"cite_ref-Landau_2-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.w=
ikipedia.org/wiki/Big_O_notation#cite_note-Landau-2"><span class=3D"cite-br=
acket">[</span>2<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
and expanded by others, collectively called <b>Bachmann=E2=80=93Landau nota=
tion</b>.  The letter O was chosen by Bachmann to stand for <i><a href=3D"h=
ttps://en.wiktionary.org/wiki/Ordnung#German" class=3D"extiw" title=3D"wikt=
:Ordnung">Ordnung</a></i>, meaning the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/=
wiki/Order_of_approximation" title=3D"Order of approximation">order of appr=
oximation</a>.
</p><p>In <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Computer_science" title=
=3D"Computer science">computer science</a>, big O notation is used to <a hr=
ef=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Computational_complexity_theory" title=
=3D"Computational complexity theory">classify algorithms</a> according to h=
ow their run time or space requirements
<sup id=3D"cite_ref-3" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.=
org/wiki/Big_O_notation#cite_note-3"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>a=
<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> grow as the input size grow=
s.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-:0_4-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wik=
ipedia.org/wiki/Big_O_notation#cite_note-:0-4"><span class=3D"cite-bracket"=
>[</span>3<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> =20
In <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Analytic_number_theory" title=
=3D"Analytic number theory">analytic number theory</a>, big O notation is o=
ften used to express bounds on the growth of an <a href=3D"https://en.wikip=
edia.org/wiki/Arithmetic_function" title=3D"Arithmetic function">arithmetic=
al function</a>; one well-known example is the remainder term in the <a hre=
f=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Prime_number_theorem" title=3D"Prime num=
ber theorem">prime number theorem</a>.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-iwaniec-kowalski_=
5-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Big_O_not=
ation#cite_note-iwaniec-kowalski-5"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>4<=
span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
In <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mathematical_analysis" title=3D=
"Mathematical analysis">mathematical analysis</a>, including <a href=3D"htt=
ps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Calculus" title=3D"Calculus">calculus</a>,
Big O notation is used to bound the error when truncating a <a href=3D"http=
s://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Power_series" title=3D"Power series">power series=
</a> and to express the quality
of approximation of a real or complex valued function
by a simpler function.
</p><p>Often, big O notation characterizes functions according to their gro=
wth rates as the variable becomes large: different functions with the same =
asymptotic growth rate may be represented using the same O notation. The le=
tter O is used because the growth rate of a function is also referred to as=
 the <b>order of the function</b>.  A description of a function in terms of=
 big O notation only provides an <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/U=
pper_bound" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Upper bound">upper bound</a> on =
the growth rate of the function.
</p><p>Associated with big O notation are several related notations, using =
the symbols <span class=3D"mwe-math-element mwe-math-element-inline"><span =
class=3D"mwe-math-mathml-inline mwe-math-mathml-a11y" style=3D"display: non=
e;"><math xmlns=3D"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" alttext=3D"{\display=
