            <mi class=3D"MJX-tex-caligraphic" mathvariant=3D"script">O</mi>
          </mrow>
        </mrow>
      </mstyle>
    </mrow>
    <annotation encoding=3D"application/x-tex">{\displaystyle {\mathcal {O}=
}}</annotation>
  </semantics>
</math></span><img src=3D"https://wikimedia.org/api/rest_v1/media/math/rend=
er/svg/d6ae2ed4058fb748a183d9ada8aea50a00d0c89f" class=3D"mwe-math-fallback=
-image-inline mw-invert skin-invert" aria-hidden=3D"true" style=3D"vertical=
-align: -0.338ex; width:1.85ex; height:2.176ex;" alt=3D"{\displaystyle {\ma=
thcal {O}}}"></span> instead.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-32" class=3D"reference"><a=
 href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Big_O_notation#cite_note-32"><span c=
lass=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>31<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></=
sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref-33" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikip=
edia.org/wiki/Big_O_notation#cite_note-33"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</=
span>32<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>The big-O originally stands for "order of" ("Ordnung", Bachmann 1894=
), and is thus a Latin letter. Neither Bachmann nor Landau ever call it "Om=
icron". The symbol was much later on (1976) viewed by Knuth as a capital <a=
 href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Omicron" title=3D"Omicron">omicron</=
a>,<sup id=3D"cite_ref-knuth_8-8" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en=
.wikipedia.org/wiki/Big_O_notation#cite_note-knuth-8"><span class=3D"cite-b=
racket">[</span>7<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> probably i=
n reference to his definition of the symbol <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia=
.org/wiki/Omega" title=3D"Omega">Omega</a>. The digit <a href=3D"https://en=
.wikipedia.org/wiki/0" title=3D"0">zero</a> should not be used.
</p>
